This week I did a thing…. 

A full out photo shoot … for myself. I needed updated headshots and just made a morning of it. Sure, I love to share stuff of me being “fancy” once in a while (cause let’s face it… I live in sweats most of the time)… BUT the real reason for sharing this is that I had the most fun doing it. The ONLY reason I had fun with this is because I had some amazing humans with me. I want to give them a shout out because they made a wildly uncomfortable situation for me, fun. I know it’s weird that I’m uncomfortable with phots and videos since like …. I’m a content creator 😅

Ok here goes: 
📸 @gaganfinephotos - this guy has been doing photos and videos for me since I started back in 2016. He reached out one day asking to help… he’s been around ever since. Stand up guy, great with kids and very patient with all my annoying requests. You need photos for anything (even family ones)… reach out to him. 

Hair and makeup by @freshface_muah : she did my makeup once somewhere … then when I knew my project was going to be on national news, I called her… she was there the next morning at 8am. I never have to worry about my makeup with her. I don’t even tell her what I want. She knows I don’t really wear makeup and I trust her expertise 😊

Styling by @thismamaneedsavacay - I don’t even know how to start with Raj. You know when you actually haven’t known someone that long but they become someone you message like daily to chat or get advice? She’s become that for me. Aside from her being my emotional support buddy …. She’s like REALLY good at what she does. When you see the fusion lengha look, know that it was ALL her. 

Also going to give a shout out to @visionroom.ca cause the place was awesome and the staff is friendly and welcoming. I will definitely be going back 🙌🏽

Ok I’m done… which look from this sneak peak is your fav?

3 things I want my kids to learn about being a Sikh…

I don’t share a lot about how Sikhi plays a role in my life here on my platform and here is why…

The criticism. 
The judgement. 
The holier than thou that tell me everything I say and do is wrong. 

Today, I don’t care about them. 

It’s Sikh Heritage Month and I’ve had the privilege to be a part of many events at various schools across the boards here in Ontario (I still have about 6 left!). As part of these presentations, I shared what aspects of being a Sikh guide my everyday life that Herpreet and I try very hard to instil in our children. I wanted to share those with you here:

	✨Seva - selfless community service. If I have an opportunity to help others in need, I do it. It’s an opportunity to serve my community and help create a better and kinder world. 
	✨Equality and social justice - I believe all people are equal. As such, it is my job to help fight back against social injustices happening to ANY group of people. 
	✨Religious Freedom - I believe in the right to practice religion freely. I believe there is one path to god. Whatever religion you connect with, is your path. 

What’s one value (religious or otherwise) that you work hard to instil in your children?

Also - where did the time go with my babies 🥺

#sikh #sikhi #sikhism #sikhheritagemonth #sikhmom #mylifeasasikh #tinasingh #momof3 #brownmom #canadianmom #sikhkids #sikhcanada

So I want to start a new series here on IG where I talk about the life of an entrepreneur…

I want to share lessons I’m learning because the lessons seem different now even though I have been an entrepreneur for pretty much my entire adult life. This time… this experience with Bold Helmets feels different. I’m also older and wiser now so I feel like I can see through a lot of things I couldn’t see through before. 

So, let’s talk about my post… but let’s start by saying no one has to show you any support. That’s the real truth. No one owes you anything… period. For those who do choose to show support, in any way they choose, I am forever grateful. 

Here is what I call “real support”:
If you have an opportunity to drop someone’s name in a room full of opportunity for them… DO IT. 

That is REAL support. It’s a very tangible way for a person to become more successful with their business and build more contacts/connections. I didn’t get anywhere without people offering me this support. There is this feeling that we may “miss out” on something if we name drop someone else… I can promise you, you won’t. When women (in particular), lift each other up, it’s good for all women. 

Let’s take influencer marketing as an example. When I am working on a campaign and I know my colleague may also be a good fit, I mention them. Most of the time what happens is that we both get a partnership and we didn’t loose anything. We just got a bigger partnership as a collective. When we work as a group to lift each other up, it’s good for all of us. 

This whole post to say that if you want to show someone real support… mention their name in a room full of opportunities for them🤍

*I’m gonna need a name for this series on IG. Leave your suggestions (and any other thoughts in the comments!)*

Before you say I’m generalizing…
Before you say how supportive the men in your life are…
Before you say they weren’t discriminating because you are a woman…

check yourself.

I’ve spent many of my years working in a very female dominated profession and I don’t think I ever felt discriminated against as a woman during that time. I felt discriminated against in other ways (that’s a story for another day), but not because I’m a woman. 

Now that I’ve entered a more public space with @BoldHelmets the discrimination feels clear and intentional. 

No, not all people discriminate against female founders. 
Yes, many men are supportive. 
Some men also think they can throw their weight around to intimidate you.

The fact is that female founders receive less venture capital funding than males. As little as 2% … but pair them with a man and that number goes up 🤔 I’m sharing this as a concrete example with research behind it as an example of what female founders face. 

Even though I’ve faced discrimination in more ways than one since taking on this project…  the support I received from women in this space has been phenomenal. 

Women in this space have been…
Perfect strangers willing to help. 
Perfect strangers saying my name in rooms full of opportunity. 
Perfect strangers who went through what I went through. 
Perfect strangers working together in the hope that one day they don’t need to prepare other women for the discrimination ahead. 

Shout out to all the women and men who have stood by my side. I hope one day I have the opportunity to give back and be a voice of support for female founders.

In today’s episode of fake it till you make it … me 😅

Well, it’s been a revolving door of illnesses at my place but I’m happy to report that I *think* we are close to the end🤞🏾 

The last two weeks really had me reflecting on being an entrepreneur and a mom. Yes, I love what I do but it can be overwhelming trying to manage both. I outsource what I can and then give myself grace for whatever I can’t do (lord knows I’m trying my best). 

As I went through the last two weeks rescheduling meetings, running to the pediatricians office and dealing with fussy kids, I felt frustrated. I felt like I had a hundred things to do for work and this was all slowing me down. 

One day I stopped and thought to myself… “wait, isn’t this why you wanted to be an entrepreneur?… to have your time in your own hands?"

That shifted things for me. 

Taking care of my kids is my biggest priority. I'm trying to build a life where I can do what needs to be done as a priority at any given time. 

All this to say… its about perspective 🙏🏽

Meet Tina Singh, a driven entrepreneur, Occupational Therapist, digital content creator, and founder of Bold Helmets. From an early age, Tina was exposed to the world of entrepreneurship through her father's business. In 2008, Tina started her own Occupational Therapy practice, providing assessment and treatment for individuals with acquired brain injury. Tina's devotion to her practice and clients led to her success in the field.

In 2015, after having her third son, Tina started creating digital family content on YouTube. Her content evolved to include advice on motherhood, entrepreneurship, and parenting through the lens of an Occupational Therapist. Tina's ability to connect with her audience has garnered a large following and has opened doors for her latest venture.

In 2023, Tina launched Bold Helmets, a project that arose from her real-life experiences as a mother. As an Occupational Therapist, Tina knew the importance of helmets in preventing head injuries, and she was determined to make sure that children of all identities had access to helmets that fit their unique needs. The idea for Bold Helmets arose from Tina's experience of not being able to find a helmet that fit over her son's patka, a Sikh head covering, when they started riding bikes, skateboards, and scooters. Her mission with Bold Helmets is to ensure that all children have access to sports equipment that works for them, and that they never have to choose between sports participation and their identity. The self-funded project was a challenge for Tina, but her commitment to her mission led her to success.

Tina's major milestones include starting her own practice in 2008, her own digital content creation business in 2015, and Bold Helmets in 2022. Despite the challenges that come with entrepreneurship, Tina's approach has always been to fully devote herself to her projects. Her mission is to ensure that all kids have access to products that work for them, so that no child has to choose between sport participation and their identity.

As you are doing your seasonal wardrobe switch, it would be great to actually get rid of those gently worn garments you no longer need. You don't need to be that person anymore 😅

On Saturday May 27th, Diabetes Canada is having a clothing drive in Mississauga from 9am-1pm! 
Here's what to do:
1. collect your gently used clothing and small household items and put them in a box or bag
2. put them in the trunk of your car
3. Head to Mississauga - 1131 Dundas street west in the Giant Tiger parking lot
4. pop your trunk and volunteers will collect your donations
5. live a life free of clutter and sleep well know that you helped divert textiles from landfills, helped fund research and helped send kids with type 1 diabetes to camp 🙌🏽

If everyone agrees with you, you don’t have a big enough sample 😣

When you are bouncing ideas off people and getting opinions, if everyone agrees with you, you have a problem. I experienced this first hand. It was a tough lesson to learn… like who doesn’t want people to agree with them? 😅

Constructive criticism helps you do better. Learning to accept constructive criticism is a whole skill. I like to sit with it. I think most people get defensive (myself included) but when you take time to sit with the feedback, it makes a world of difference. Once you have had time to sit with it, you can decide what to do with it. 

Hearing diverse opinions and feedback will make you a better person… in any industry. 

#entrepreneur #entrepreneur101 #founder #femaleentrepreneur #femalefounders #entrepreneurship #entrepreneurlife #tinasingh #womeninbusiness #lifelessons

In case you thought it was glamorous… 

It’s not. 
I mean, it can be, but not for me… yet 🙏🏽
For every order that comes down the line, I 
-build a box
-pick and pack the box
-seal the box 
-create a shipping label
-drop off to the shipping carrier

It all has to be done between the hours of 9-2 cause like … kids 😅

I’m sharing this because we can often get caught up in the comparison game. Someone is gonna watch this reel and think, “that doesn’t seem hard”…. It’s hard when you have a million other things to juggle (many things that you don’t even know how to do). It’s hard when you are responsible for sales, customer service, shipping, delivery, marketing and finances. On top of that, I have 3 kids that are my top priority, food that has to be cooked, laundry that needs to be washed and a dog who likes to cuddle. So I might share some successes and wins in this space but you should know it’s all backed by a lot of hard work. 

I’m realizing more and more why it’s so important to celebrate your wins… no matter how small. The wins (but more importantly your WHY) helps you get through the work 🙏🏽

Success lives outside your comfort zone… and so does imposter syndrome 🤔

You know that anxiety you feel when you try something new?
I been feeling it on the daily. 

Yesterday, I had a booth for @boldhelmets
at a Canada day celebration in Brampton and the feeling of “I don’t belong here” kept creeping in. 
I tried to ignore it, but it was there all day. 
It was there even though I met so many wonderful people. 
It was there even though people praised me for my work. 
It was there even though I had endless family and friend support throughout the day. 
It was there because I am so far outside my comfort zone with this project that I can’t even see my comfort zone anymore. 

I’m gonna just sit here in this discomfort because I know that success lives outside your comfort zone. 

If you are feeling “imposter syndrome” it’s probably because you are doing good work, fighting the good fight or trying something new. 

BUT…

Imposter syndrome doesn’t have to be the enemy. 
It can be the reminder that you are taking risks. 
It can be the reminder that you are learning. 
It can be the reminder that you are growing and changing. 
In the end, isn’t that what we are supposed to do in life?

I’ve never had a job that repeatedly reminded me that I don’t know things 😅

Learning on the job and the hours and dedication it takes can often make entrepreneurship a lonely place. You are unlikely to be around people who understand your struggles. If you are like me and 40+ your friends are entering a new era of their lives (usually with more financial freedom and kids who are aren’t super young) … and it’s a great one but you can’t quite join in. 

I invested in my business. I invested in my dream. I don’t regret it for a second but when I think about what our summer would have looked like if I hadn’t taken this on… I do feel a bit bad. 

This is why I say this journey is lonely. You will meet very few people who can relate to your situation, your new venture and your passion. It’s not you… it’s just a normal part of the journey. 

If you are lucky enough to find people who understand you, hold on to them for dear life. 

Tag the people who have been your support in entrepreneurship or a goal of some kind. 

Thank you @sonya_gill and @also_sophia for letting me voice note you my meltdowns any time of day 🤍

For 2023, instead of resolutions, I had decided on a word that I was going to let guide me… 

As we wrap up August and approach a new school year (I always call September the “mom new year because it’s a great time to reevaluate and set new goals🎉) I wanted to take a moment to reflect on my word of the year for 2023. Believe it or not, my word was BOLD. 

I let this word guide me during some hard times and I let this word guide me when I pivoted on the name of my business. 

Normally, by this time in the year, I experience guilt for not focusing enough on my goals/word of the year. 

This year is different. 
I worked as hard as I could. 
I stepped so far out of my comfort zone that I can’t see it anymore. 

There is always more work to do but today, on the last day of August (which also happens to be a significant day for my business), I celebrate being BOLD and how far I have come. 

I’d love to know what your word of the year is (if you remember it… most years I forget 😅)

It’s easy to brush past what we want for everyone else’s joy. 
I know these are donuts but they are more than donuts. Let me explain:

I wanted to make sure I had a chance to get pumpkin donuts from the farm market but the kids were enjoying themselves in the play area for so long that the store was about to close. Herpreet tried to hurry everyone out so I could get these donuts and then filmed it. 

It would have been easy for me to miss this one thing I wanted but I know I would have felt some resentment later. Let’s be real, these are donuts and not getting them wouldn’t be the end of the world but not getting them would have been another reminder of the daily sacrifices we make as mothers. 

What’s my point? After 12 years of parenting I finally feel like it’s ok for me to also ask for the things I need… even if that thing is as simple as pumpkin donuts.

You matter. 
Your needs matter. 
Get the donuts.

Over the last few weeks i’ve had more than two people tell me to have “confidence” in what I’m doing…

I sat with the feedback and realized that me asking for help, feeling confused about things and not knowing if i’m doing the right thing was being equated with not being confident. If I’ve never done something before, it’s gonna take me time to figure it out… and that’s ok. 

I’m confident I will figure it out. 
I’m confident I will make the right choices in the end. 
I’m confident that I can deliver on the work I set out to do. 
I’m confident that not being so sure of things while you figure stuff out is normal. 
I’m confident that I am able.
